WEBVTT

00:01.460 --> 00:06.006
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:06.006 --> 00:08.175
[cauldron bubbling]

00:08.175 --> 00:12.095
<i>- Here in The Forge, we build</i>
<i>blades from history...</i>

00:12.095 --> 00:15.849
<i>but sometimes we're inspired</i>
<i>by things...</i>

00:15.849 --> 00:17.851
<i>more frightening...</i>

00:17.851 --> 00:20.103
like horror movies.

00:20.103 --> 00:22.606
Tonight
our Slasher Challenge...

00:22.606 --> 00:25.192
- In a slasher film,
you don't go, "Ha!"

00:25.192 --> 00:28.528
'Cause everybody goes what?
- "Ha!"

00:28.528 --> 00:31.365
<i>- Four bladesmiths bring</i>
<i>their skills to The Forge.</i>

00:31.365 --> 00:33.700
It's getting scarier
and scarier in here.

00:33.700 --> 00:35.577
<i>Which one will make</i>
<i>it out alive...</i>

00:35.577 --> 00:37.162
You'll flip.

00:37.162 --> 00:39.039
Everything flips down here.
[laughing goofily]

00:39.039 --> 00:41.333
<i>To become</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion?</i>

00:41.333 --> 00:43.210
<i>[shrieking]</i>

00:44.753 --> 00:51.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:54.054 --> 00:55.639
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>David Sowards-Emmerd.</i>

00:55.639 --> 00:57.266
<i>I'm from Bend, Oregon.</i>

00:57.266 --> 00:58.642
Before I started bladesmithing
full-time,

00:58.642 --> 01:01.061
<i>I got a PhD in astrophysics.</i>

01:01.061 --> 01:02.938
I know steel.
I know how to move steel.

01:02.938 --> 01:05.357
I know how to treat steel
with heat.

01:05.357 --> 01:07.276
I can do this.

01:07.276 --> 01:08.694
<i>- My name's Tim Miller.</i>

01:08.694 --> 01:10.737
I'm from Oak Harbor,
Washington.

01:10.737 --> 01:13.282
<i>My brother, Mike Miller,</i>
<i>recently competed</i>

01:13.282 --> 01:16.451
<i>in the veteran's competition,</i>
<i>and I'd like to win.</i>

01:16.451 --> 01:17.995
That way, I can have
bragging rights

01:17.995 --> 01:19.413
over the fact
he came in second.

01:19.413 --> 01:21.665
[laughs]

01:21.665 --> 01:24.209
<i>- My name is Chase Register.</i>
<i>I'm 20 years old.</i>

01:24.209 --> 01:25.919
And I'm from Alachua, Florida.

01:25.919 --> 01:28.505
<i>When I was younger,</i>
<i>I really got into</i>

01:28.505 --> 01:30.549
swords and shields
and armor and knights

01:30.549 --> 01:32.134
<i>and anything to do with that.</i>

01:32.134 --> 01:34.303
<i>So that has influenced</i>
<i>my smithing.</i>

01:34.303 --> 01:36.388
I'm definitely ready
for this competition.

01:36.388 --> 01:38.265
<i>- My name is Brandon Williams.</i>

01:38.265 --> 01:39.891
I am from Blackfoot, Idaho,
and I've been making knives

01:39.891 --> 01:41.435
for about seven years now.

01:41.435 --> 01:43.270
I'd like to make these great
big blades

01:43.270 --> 01:44.813
and call 'em zombie killers

01:44.813 --> 01:46.857
because it gets people's
attention.

01:46.857 --> 01:48.525
<i>I'd like to be able to,</i>
<i>you know,</i>

01:48.525 --> 01:50.027
<i>say I can take a tree down</i>

01:50.027 --> 01:51.820
and then a zombie's head,
of course.

01:51.820 --> 01:53.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:53.405 --> 01:55.741
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:55.741 --> 01:57.117
You're here
for three timed rounds

01:57.117 --> 01:58.910
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:58.910 --> 02:00.537
specifically designed
to push

02:00.537 --> 02:02.289
every aspect of your skills
to the limit

02:02.289 --> 02:04.249
in front of
a panel of expert judges

02:04.249 --> 02:05.709
who will determine
which of you

02:05.709 --> 02:07.669
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

02:07.669 --> 02:09.963
leaving here with
a check for $10,000.

02:09.963 --> 02:11.548
Let's meet your judges now.

02:11.548 --> 02:13.300
Up first, two-time
"Forged in Fire" champion

02:13.300 --> 02:16.053
and fan favorite, Ben Abbott.

02:16.053 --> 02:19.264
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

02:19.264 --> 02:21.850
And last, edged-weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

02:21.850 --> 02:23.769
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:23.769 --> 02:26.813
Bladesmiths, in today's
first round of competition,

02:26.813 --> 02:31.151
you gentlemen will be making
one of my favorite things--

02:31.151 --> 02:35.072
a slasher blade
for a slasher movie.

02:35.072 --> 02:37.491
I mean,
who can forget movies like

02:37.491 --> 02:38.992
Ghostface killer
from "Scream"?

02:38.992 --> 02:40.452
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:40.452 --> 02:42.120
Or Michael Myers
from "Halloween"?

02:42.120 --> 02:44.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:44.081 --> 02:47.626
And, of course, Jason Voorhees
from "Friday the 13th"?

02:47.626 --> 02:50.796
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:50.796 --> 02:53.131
Gentlemen, in this
first round of competition,

02:53.131 --> 02:55.175
you will make a sharp
and terrifying,

02:55.175 --> 02:57.302
horror-film-inspired
slasher blade

02:57.302 --> 02:59.429
in your own signature style.

02:59.429 --> 03:00.847
The length of your blades

03:00.847 --> 03:02.974
must be between
12 and 15 inches.

03:02.974 --> 03:04.893
In the second round,
you will be attaching handles

03:04.893 --> 03:07.020
to those blades to turn them
into fully functional weapons

03:07.020 --> 03:09.606
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:09.606 --> 03:12.192
in a hockey mask chop...

03:12.192 --> 03:16.655
and for edge retention
in a leather mask slice.

03:16.655 --> 03:19.032
Now it's time you pick
your steel

03:19.032 --> 03:22.119
from our bubbling cauldron
over here.

03:22.119 --> 03:23.954
- Will tells us we got
to pick this steel

03:23.954 --> 03:25.664
out of a smoking cauldron,

03:25.664 --> 03:28.834
<i>and I'm very nervous</i>
<i>to see what I get.</i>

03:28.834 --> 03:30.961
- Chase, you're up first.
Choose your steel.

03:32.629 --> 03:36.383
You have selected
a ball bearing of 52100 steel.

03:36.383 --> 03:39.052
- I'm worried
that my steel is so thick.

03:39.052 --> 03:42.389
- Tim, you're up next.
Choose your steel.

03:42.389 --> 03:45.434
It's a coil of
5160 spring steel.

03:45.434 --> 03:47.644
It's good steel.
It's gonna be challenging.

03:47.644 --> 03:48.979
David, you're up.

03:48.979 --> 03:51.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:51.982 --> 03:55.861
You got the Devil's fingers
of 1095 square stock.

03:55.861 --> 03:57.779
Brandon,
go ahead and choose your steel.

03:57.779 --> 04:01.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:01.533 --> 04:04.786
All right, Brandon,
you've got the W1 round stock.

04:04.786 --> 04:06.413
What do you think?
- Hells, yeah, man.

04:06.413 --> 04:08.081
- Bladesmiths,

04:08.081 --> 04:09.875
you have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

04:09.875 --> 04:12.669
You have three hours
to forge your blades.

04:12.669 --> 04:14.087
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:14.087 --> 04:16.131
Your ten-minute design window
starts...

04:16.131 --> 04:17.924
now.

04:17.924 --> 04:20.510
- No running with pitchforks.
[both laugh]

04:20.510 --> 04:25.348
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:25.348 --> 04:27.559
<i>- I like to make</i>
<i>camp knife choppers.</i>

04:27.559 --> 04:31.062
A chopper's a good knife
for a killer for the tasks.

04:31.062 --> 04:33.648
<i>One of the tasks is chopping--</i>
<i>no-brainer--</i>

04:33.648 --> 04:35.776
<i>and the other task of slicing</i>
<i>through a leather mask.</i>

04:35.776 --> 04:37.569
It should do a nice job
for that, too.

04:37.569 --> 04:39.321
- Everybody is hiding
their work.

04:39.321 --> 04:40.781
- Like somebody eating
in prison.

04:40.781 --> 04:42.449
Like...
- [laughs]

04:42.449 --> 04:44.409
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:44.409 --> 04:46.661
<i>- I use spring steel a lot</i>
<i>because it's tough</i>

04:46.661 --> 04:48.330
<i>and it's durable.</i>

04:48.330 --> 04:49.956
<i>I'm doing two designs.</i>

04:49.956 --> 04:52.209
<i>One's a slasher-style</i>
<i>chef's knife.</i>

04:52.209 --> 04:53.919
<i>The other one's</i>
<i>a drop point hunter.</i>

04:53.919 --> 04:56.379
<i>I think that's iconic</i>
<i>in slasher movies.</i>

04:56.379 --> 04:58.590
Can't decide on which one
I want to do.

04:58.590 --> 05:01.259
<i>I'll let the metal tell me</i>
<i>when I start working it.</i>

05:01.259 --> 05:03.804
- Doug,
your favorite slasher movie?

05:03.804 --> 05:06.097
- "Friday the 13th,"
of course, the series of that.

05:06.097 --> 05:08.058
If I'm not having sex,
nobody else is.

05:08.058 --> 05:09.601
[laughter]

05:09.601 --> 05:11.436
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:11.436 --> 05:13.522
<i>- I immediately thought</i>
<i>of the machete</i>

05:13.522 --> 05:15.524
<i>from "Friday the 13th."</i>

05:15.524 --> 05:18.235
It's a really interesting
weapon, really cool weapon

05:18.235 --> 05:20.403
<i>that you get to see a lot</i>
<i>throughout the film.</i>

05:20.403 --> 05:23.365
<i>Little bit modified</i>
<i>from a normal machete.</i>

05:23.365 --> 05:25.700
<i>The tip was a little bit</i>
<i>more rounded,</i>

05:25.700 --> 05:28.537
<i>but I wanted a large belly</i>
<i>for the challenges</i>

05:28.537 --> 05:30.747
<i>that we were facing</i>
<i>with the knives.</i>

05:30.747 --> 05:33.250
- What kind of blade
would you make--slasher blade?

05:33.250 --> 05:35.168
- Man, the Charay,
the Khyber knife.

05:35.168 --> 05:37.254
<i>It's a kitchen knife,</i>
<i>but it's made to lop limbs.</i>

05:37.254 --> 05:39.130
- Doug, what would you do?

05:39.130 --> 05:40.924
- Stick with a machete,
because nobody cuts trees

05:40.924 --> 05:43.260
with kitchen knives.
[laughter]

05:43.260 --> 05:45.971
<i>- When Will told us</i>
<i>that we were gonna be making</i>

05:45.971 --> 05:48.598
a slasher from a horror movie,
I was so excited.

05:48.598 --> 05:51.268
It couldn't have been
a better match for me.

05:51.268 --> 05:53.228
<i>My blade's really</i>
<i>kind of a cross</i>

05:53.228 --> 05:55.522
<i>between a machete and kukri,</i>

05:55.522 --> 05:58.275
<i>but it has a little</i>
<i>bit of recurve in it.</i>

05:58.275 --> 06:01.778
- Bladesmiths, your ten-minute
design window has closed.

06:01.778 --> 06:04.531
Your three-hour forge
time starts... now.

06:04.531 --> 06:06.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:06.783 --> 06:09.578
We've got four smiths working
four different types of steels,

06:09.578 --> 06:12.038
four different shapes,
creating four different

06:12.038 --> 06:14.791
signature slasher blades.

06:14.791 --> 06:16.543
Each of these steels
has its own

06:16.543 --> 06:18.461
unique set of complications.

06:18.461 --> 06:20.755
- I'd say the one
that we've seen the smiths

06:20.755 --> 06:22.966
have the most problem
with is the 52100.

06:22.966 --> 06:24.759
- The ball bearing--
not only is the shape

06:24.759 --> 06:26.928
hard to deal with,
but it's also

06:26.928 --> 06:30.181
very temperamental
when it comes to temperature.

06:30.181 --> 06:32.475
- Yep.
- [laughs]

06:32.475 --> 06:34.978
- The only concern is I have
is my ball bearing's so thick,

06:34.978 --> 06:37.898
it's taking a long time to come
up to forging temperature.

06:37.898 --> 06:40.692
Oh, yeah,
now we're getting somewhere.

06:40.692 --> 06:43.028
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:43.028 --> 06:44.905
- I cut the coil
basically in half.

06:44.905 --> 06:46.656
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:46.656 --> 06:48.992
<i>My next step is to get</i>
<i>it in the forge.</i>

06:48.992 --> 06:50.952
Ooh, I think I've burnt
a little hair.

06:50.952 --> 06:53.371
Once it's hot,
I can start uncoiling it.

06:53.371 --> 06:55.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:55.999 --> 06:58.043
- There you go.
That's the way to do it.

06:58.043 --> 07:00.128
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:00.128 --> 07:02.505
<i>- First thing I want to do is</i>
<i>put it in the forge</i>

07:02.505 --> 07:05.175
and got to wait a few
to let it to warm up.

07:05.175 --> 07:07.510
Holy [bleep], that's hot.
- Hot glove.

07:07.510 --> 07:09.763
- I should have put
a longer handle on it,

07:09.763 --> 07:11.723
'cause that handle's getting
hot as hell.

07:11.723 --> 07:13.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:13.892 --> 07:16.144
<i>- I've got 1095 steel.</i>
<i>That's what I usually use.</i>

07:16.144 --> 07:17.771
Easy to heat-treat,
good to forge.

07:17.771 --> 07:19.439
<i>Good steel all around.</i>

07:19.439 --> 07:21.274
- He's got a plugged nozzle.

07:21.274 --> 07:24.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:24.986 --> 07:27.238
- All right.

07:27.238 --> 07:28.865
- David's using all
of his steel.

07:28.865 --> 07:30.325
He's got both of those billets
welded together.

07:30.325 --> 07:32.077
- There you go.

07:32.077 --> 07:35.163
- I'm going to forge-weld
the two pieces together,

07:35.163 --> 07:37.165
since I believe that's
what I need material-wise

07:37.165 --> 07:39.584
to make the blade
I'd like to make.

07:39.584 --> 07:44.297
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:44.297 --> 07:46.383
First forge weld took.
Now I just stretch it out.

07:46.383 --> 07:47.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:47.842 --> 07:49.803
<i>Big Blue.</i>
<i>That's just fun.</i>

07:49.803 --> 07:51.680
I love power hammers.

07:51.680 --> 07:53.765
They're just a lot of power,
and... [chuckles]

07:53.765 --> 07:55.392
<i>It's a great tool.</i>

07:55.392 --> 07:56.935
♪ ♪

07:56.935 --> 07:59.396
- If you're gonna create
a slasher blade

07:59.396 --> 08:01.648
from scratch
with a signature style,

08:01.648 --> 08:04.275
why not put some barbs
on the back of it?

08:04.275 --> 08:06.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:06.444 --> 08:09.781
<i>- I was enjoying the press,</i>
<i>and I didn't pay attention</i>

08:09.781 --> 08:12.117
to how thin I had already
gotten it.

08:12.117 --> 08:14.536
She's gonna be
what she's gonna be.

08:14.536 --> 08:18.123
- Look, Tim has drawn
that bar out even further.

08:18.123 --> 08:19.708
[hammer pounding]

08:19.708 --> 08:22.043
- Long and skinny.

08:22.043 --> 08:24.421
- [bleep], that's a long-ass
[bleep] blade.

08:24.421 --> 08:26.339
Getting the blade too thin,
it limits you

08:26.339 --> 08:29.134
to what you can actually
do with it.

08:29.134 --> 08:32.429
So I either restart
or continue where I was at

08:32.429 --> 08:34.139
<i>with a thinner profile,</i>

08:34.139 --> 08:36.099
and I chose to go
with the thinner profile.

08:36.099 --> 08:38.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:38.852 --> 08:42.272
<i>Apparently I'm using the same</i>
<i>anvil and forge as my brother.</i>

08:42.272 --> 08:43.606
Should be interesting.

08:43.606 --> 08:45.650
Hopefully it works
better for me.

08:45.650 --> 08:48.361
- Tim looks like he's drifting
some holes in his tang.

08:48.361 --> 08:51.114
<i>- I've never punched</i>
<i>handle holes before,</i>

08:51.114 --> 08:53.533
but I didn't want to deal
with trying to drill 'em.

08:53.533 --> 08:57.412
<i>Drilling hardened steel</i>
<i>is difficult,</i>

08:57.412 --> 08:59.039
<i>especially 5160.</i>

08:59.039 --> 09:00.415
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:00.415 --> 09:02.500
- Bladesmiths!

09:02.500 --> 09:05.378
You have just
90 minutes remaining

09:05.378 --> 09:08.006
to finish your signature
slasher blades!

09:08.006 --> 09:09.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:09.841 --> 09:11.676
<i>- I love heating the steel up,</i>
<i>moving it</i>

09:11.676 --> 09:13.636
<i>and beating it with a hammer.</i>

09:13.636 --> 09:16.181
It's a stress reliever
for me.

09:16.181 --> 09:17.932
<i>I've got a lot of steel here,</i>

09:17.932 --> 09:20.435
<i>so I think I can afford</i>
<i>to cut off a little bit.</i>

09:20.435 --> 09:22.187
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:22.187 --> 09:24.981
<i>When I'm cutting off steel</i>
<i>under pressure,</i>

09:24.981 --> 09:27.192
I'm hoping I'm doing
the right thing.

09:27.192 --> 09:29.110
- Brandon's on
an 8-inch contact wheel

09:29.110 --> 09:31.404
just working on his profile.

09:31.404 --> 09:33.740
Looks like he's putting in
a little bit of a curve

09:33.740 --> 09:35.867
in the belly of that blade,

09:35.867 --> 09:39.454
so we'll have that nice,
heavy, kukri-esque, fat tip.

09:39.454 --> 09:41.706
- And I love the theme--
the slashers.

09:41.706 --> 09:43.917
It's awesome.
I'm so excited right now.

09:43.917 --> 09:48.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:48.129 --> 09:50.465
- I'm forging, and there's
an excess amount of steel

09:50.465 --> 09:52.300
that I'm not even touching.

09:52.300 --> 09:55.261
- It looks like
Chase's plan is to just

09:55.261 --> 09:56.971
hammer that section off.

09:56.971 --> 09:59.015
- [laughing]

09:59.015 --> 10:00.725
<i>- As I'm working down</i>
<i>the handle,</i>

10:00.725 --> 10:02.852
I eventually transition
to chopping that off...

10:02.852 --> 10:05.105
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:05.105 --> 10:07.440
Which was a mistake.

10:07.440 --> 10:09.400
I realize that I've cut off

10:09.400 --> 10:11.528
almost every extra bit
that I had

10:11.528 --> 10:14.197
<i>and that my handle</i>
<i>is way too thin.</i>

10:14.197 --> 10:15.865
- Do you think the pressure
of competition

10:15.865 --> 10:17.826
is maybe forcing Chase
to rush the process?

10:17.826 --> 10:19.410
- Yeah, absolutely.

10:19.410 --> 10:21.121
- I'm getting frustrated
at myself.

10:21.121 --> 10:23.706
<i>I'm sitting here</i>
<i>with a problem that I made.</i>

10:23.706 --> 10:26.167
However, I realize
that I left thickness

10:26.167 --> 10:28.002
<i>in my blade,</i>
<i>which I'm able to draw</i>

10:28.002 --> 10:29.879
<i>into a much better handle.</i>

10:29.879 --> 10:32.173
- What do you think
of his tang design?

10:32.173 --> 10:34.342
- Tang looks pretty small,
to be honest.

10:34.342 --> 10:36.719
It's gonna be
hard to hold on to.

10:36.719 --> 10:39.681
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:39.681 --> 10:41.683
<i>- I think I'm ahead of time.</i>

10:41.683 --> 10:43.560
I was hoping to have the blade
to shape with an hour left,

10:43.560 --> 10:45.353
<i>and I'm 90% of the shape</i>
<i>right now.</i>

10:45.353 --> 10:47.147
I've got it at the profile
I want,

10:47.147 --> 10:49.566
and then before heat treat,
I want to grind it.

10:49.566 --> 10:52.360
Just get a little bit more
of a finish on it.

10:52.360 --> 10:53.862
- David--he's really set up.

10:53.862 --> 10:55.238
I would just love
to have seen him quench

10:55.238 --> 10:56.990
and then go to the grinder.

10:56.990 --> 10:58.867
- Yeah, quenching the blade
while it's thick--

10:58.867 --> 11:02.287
that thicker profile
is gonna hold it straighter.

11:02.287 --> 11:03.997
You're gonna have less warping.

11:03.997 --> 11:05.707
<i>- I'm really happy</i>
<i>with how it's going.</i>

11:05.707 --> 11:07.625
<i>It's grinding really quick</i>
<i>and real good.</i>

11:07.625 --> 11:09.878
<i>I've got more than enough time</i>
<i>to do the quench.</i>

11:09.878 --> 11:12.088
So I think,
"Well, maybe I can drill

11:12.088 --> 11:14.257
<i>some holes</i>
<i>in the handle as well."</i>

11:14.257 --> 11:16.551
Everything's going great
at this point.

11:16.551 --> 11:18.720
- David over here
on the drill press,

11:18.720 --> 11:20.471
setting up to drill
some holes

11:20.471 --> 11:22.432
to get ready for round two.

11:22.432 --> 11:23.766
- You know, you got to get
through round one

11:23.766 --> 11:25.643
to get to round two, you know.

11:25.643 --> 11:28.813
- And then I just really
crank down on it in the vise.

11:28.813 --> 11:31.065
[metal clanks]

11:31.065 --> 11:32.901
- Oh, man. Oh, man.
- Oh, my God!

11:32.901 --> 11:33.818
- Oh, man.

11:36.487 --> 11:38.114
- Oh, no.

11:38.114 --> 11:39.991
- And I turn around,
and I see my blade

11:39.991 --> 11:41.993
in two pieces on the floor
and one more piece

11:41.993 --> 11:44.454
on the drill press,
and just, "Oh, [bleep].

11:44.454 --> 11:45.622
<i>How'd this happen?"</i>

11:45.622 --> 11:47.415
- David kept bringing

11:47.415 --> 11:49.167
that billet up to temperature,

11:49.167 --> 11:50.793
and, I mean,
it was smoking hot

11:50.793 --> 11:52.253
when he was setting
those welds.

11:52.253 --> 11:54.756
Maybe there was a flaw
in that steel

11:54.756 --> 11:57.133
that David created
when he forged it out.

11:57.133 --> 11:58.301
- Could be.

11:58.301 --> 12:00.345
- Hmm. Well...

12:00.345 --> 12:02.096
The first thought is,
"I'm done.

12:02.096 --> 12:03.973
There's nothing I can do
to fix this."

12:03.973 --> 12:06.559
And then I said, "Well,
I've got 30 minutes left.

12:06.559 --> 12:08.186
I'm gonna see what I can do."

12:08.186 --> 12:10.313
I guess off to the MIG welder.

12:10.313 --> 12:12.523
So I take it over
to the welding table,

12:12.523 --> 12:15.693
and I try to put the pieces
together as best as I can.

12:15.693 --> 12:17.195
- Good,
he's at the welding table.

12:17.195 --> 12:18.655
- You know what?
I say go for it. Keep going.

12:18.655 --> 12:20.490
- You bet.
- You go in there,

12:20.490 --> 12:21.824
weld it together,
'cause you don't know

12:21.824 --> 12:23.201
how the other blades
are gonna be,

12:23.201 --> 12:24.911
parameters or anything else.

12:24.911 --> 12:26.955
He's got a fighting chance
if he acts on it now.

12:26.955 --> 12:29.207
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:29.207 --> 12:31.125
<i>- When I'm warming</i>
<i>this blade up,</i>

12:31.125 --> 12:33.711
<i>I want to make sure that</i>
<i>the edge gets really hot,</i>

12:33.711 --> 12:36.047
but I want to have good color
throughout the blade

12:36.047 --> 12:37.340
before I quench.

12:37.340 --> 12:40.134
<i>The quench is, I think,</i>

12:40.134 --> 12:41.970
<i>the most important step</i>
<i>in making a blade,</i>

12:41.970 --> 12:44.806
because when you get
that steel red hot

12:44.806 --> 12:46.349
<i>and you dip it in the oil,</i>

12:46.349 --> 12:49.269
it kind of puts
the blade's soul into it.

12:49.269 --> 12:50.937
<i>But you never know</i>
<i>what's gonna happen</i>

12:50.937 --> 12:52.188
<i>when you put it in that oil.</i>

12:52.188 --> 12:54.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:54.983 --> 12:56.150
<i>I pull it out of the oil...</i>

12:56.150 --> 12:57.694
That'll work.

12:57.694 --> 12:59.904
And the color looks
perfect to me.

12:59.904 --> 13:01.656
Oh, yeah.

13:01.656 --> 13:02.949
<i>A hardened blade.</i>
<i>I got a hardened blade.</i>

13:02.949 --> 13:04.784
Hell, yeah.

13:04.784 --> 13:08.371
Three hours ago, this was
a piece of W1 round stock

13:08.371 --> 13:10.081
<i>welded to a pitchfork,</i>

13:10.081 --> 13:13.418
<i>and now it's</i>
<i>a badass-looking blade.</i>

13:13.418 --> 13:15.044
- Tim's blade, to my eye,

13:15.044 --> 13:17.046
looks a little bit
on the rougher side.

13:17.046 --> 13:18.881
It's nowhere near as finished
and good-looking

13:18.881 --> 13:20.091
as Brandon's blade
at this point.

13:20.091 --> 13:22.051
- Right.

13:22.051 --> 13:23.803
<i>- I start grinding,</i>
<i>and I'm enjoying it,</i>

13:23.803 --> 13:24.971
<i>getting into the zone.</i>

13:24.971 --> 13:26.556
<i>Look up at the clock.</i>

13:26.556 --> 13:28.725
<i>Man, I only have</i>
<i>30 minutes left.</i>

13:28.725 --> 13:31.185
I think it's about time
to go get her heat-treated.

13:31.185 --> 13:32.979
<i>It's real critical</i>
<i>in that stage.</i>

13:32.979 --> 13:34.856
<i>I hope she doesn't crack on me</i>

13:34.856 --> 13:36.941
'cause it's a little too late
to start a new one.

13:36.941 --> 13:39.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:39.152 --> 13:40.695
Go to pull it out
the first time,

13:40.695 --> 13:42.071
<i>get a fireball.</i>

13:42.071 --> 13:44.157
<i>Back in the oil I go.</i>

13:44.157 --> 13:47.326
Go to pull it out a second
time, get another fireball.

13:47.326 --> 13:50.038
I finally got it deep enough in
the third time

13:50.038 --> 13:52.457
so I didn't get a fireball
when I pulled it out.

13:52.457 --> 13:54.834
<i>I look at the edges,</i>
<i>and I'm like,</i>

13:54.834 --> 13:57.128
"Man, I got lucky.
She's nice and straight."

13:57.128 --> 13:58.588
<i>[chuckles]</i>

13:58.588 --> 14:02.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:02.842 --> 14:04.677
- I'm trying to stay out
of my own head,

14:04.677 --> 14:06.345
<i>not psyching myself out.</i>

14:06.345 --> 14:08.806
- Chase.
- Oh, thank you.

14:08.806 --> 14:10.558
<i>Get everything heat-treated,</i>
<i>nice and hard.</i>

14:10.558 --> 14:12.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:12.518 --> 14:14.729
[metal scraping]

14:14.729 --> 14:16.397
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:16.397 --> 14:18.149
Sounds hard to me.

14:18.149 --> 14:20.026
- David's not out of this,

14:20.026 --> 14:22.570
but he has suffered
catastrophic damage

14:22.570 --> 14:24.280
to his blade.

14:24.280 --> 14:26.783
But he didn't pitch a fit.
He didn't curse.

14:26.783 --> 14:29.285
He policed up his materials,
went right over

14:29.285 --> 14:31.704
to the welding machine,
and got back to work.

14:31.704 --> 14:34.373
That's what this competition
is all about.

14:34.373 --> 14:35.875
<i>- I've got it back in</i>
<i>the forge.</i>

14:35.875 --> 14:37.627
I want to try to take
an extra heat or two

14:37.627 --> 14:39.295
just to get it straight again
now that I have these

14:39.295 --> 14:40.755
big blobs on the
side of my blade.

14:40.755 --> 14:42.840
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:42.840 --> 14:44.759
- Dave just quenched.

14:44.759 --> 14:46.928
Be straight. Be straight.

14:46.928 --> 14:49.013
<i>- So I quench,</i>
<i>and it's straight,</i>

14:49.013 --> 14:50.598
and I still have time left,

14:50.598 --> 14:53.184
<i>so I try to grind off</i>
<i>those welds.</i>

14:53.184 --> 14:56.104
- Five, four, three,

14:56.104 --> 14:58.439
two, one.

14:58.439 --> 15:00.691
Bladesmiths, shut down your
machines. Drop your tools.

15:00.691 --> 15:04.070
This first round
of slasher competition is over.

15:04.070 --> 15:05.696
[applause]

15:05.696 --> 15:07.615
<i>- Time's up.</i>
<i>I've put my blade down.</i>

15:07.615 --> 15:10.284
And I'm just thinking
I'm done.

15:10.284 --> 15:12.036
- All right, bladesmiths.

15:12.036 --> 15:13.329
Now it's time
for the judges to take

15:13.329 --> 15:14.872
a closer look
at your work.

15:14.872 --> 15:16.374
Brandon, you're up first.

15:16.374 --> 15:18.501
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:18.501 --> 15:20.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:20.753 --> 15:22.255
- Well, Brandon, first off,
this is a really

15:22.255 --> 15:23.965
good-looking knife.
- Thank you.

15:23.965 --> 15:25.842
- The handle is quite long.

15:25.842 --> 15:27.593
I mean, I can almost two-hand
this thing, you know.

15:27.593 --> 15:29.178
The big issue I have
with your knife

15:29.178 --> 15:31.764
is there are two pretty major
cracks in it.

15:31.764 --> 15:33.516
<i>There's one out by the edge,</i>

15:33.516 --> 15:36.936
<i>and there's another crack</i>
<i>along the spine.</i>

15:36.936 --> 15:38.563
But aside from that,

15:38.563 --> 15:40.148
you got a nice finish
on there.

15:40.148 --> 15:41.899
Well done.
- Thank you.

15:41.899 --> 15:44.318
- Chase, please present
your blade to the judges.

15:44.318 --> 15:46.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.779 --> 15:49.323
- I love the shape
of the blade,

15:49.323 --> 15:52.285
but this knife handle is kind
of a self-unloader.

15:52.285 --> 15:54.912
If I swing this,
there's just no retention.

15:54.912 --> 15:56.414
I would love to see,
if you move forward,

15:56.414 --> 15:59.333
something dealt
with this back end.

15:59.333 --> 16:00.793
- All right, Tim,
please present

16:00.793 --> 16:02.628
your work to the judges.

16:02.628 --> 16:04.714
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.714 --> 16:07.091
<i>- That's an intimidating</i>
<i>design that you have there.</i>

16:07.091 --> 16:10.678
Definitely reminiscent of what
a slasher movie should have,

16:10.678 --> 16:12.597
but there's a lot of refinement

16:12.597 --> 16:14.223
that needs to be done
to your blade right here.

16:14.223 --> 16:16.267
As you can see,
it's uneven a lot of parts.

16:16.267 --> 16:18.436
Your blade edge goes this way,
and then there's a dip,

16:18.436 --> 16:20.146
<i>and it gets wider.</i>

16:20.146 --> 16:22.023
Moving forward,
I'm sure you can probably

16:22.023 --> 16:24.567
find ways to straighten
that out and refine the blade

16:24.567 --> 16:26.319
because it has the makings

16:26.319 --> 16:28.821
of a very intimidating
and slasher-like blade.

16:28.821 --> 16:30.448
Good job.

16:30.448 --> 16:31.699
- All right, David,
you're up next.

16:31.699 --> 16:33.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:33.951 --> 16:35.661
<i>- Your blade shape</i>
<i>came together,</i>

16:35.661 --> 16:37.788
and your weld looks
really nice.

16:37.788 --> 16:39.290
I was really surprised
when this broke.

16:39.290 --> 16:40.958
All I can think is that
you went

16:40.958 --> 16:43.419
into the forge a lot
and super-heated

16:43.419 --> 16:45.338
that blade to get
that weld to stick.

16:45.338 --> 16:48.174
Unfortunately, we still have

16:48.174 --> 16:50.509
<i>other major cracks</i>
<i>right where all</i>

16:50.509 --> 16:52.178
<i>the stress is gonna be</i>
<i>on a chopper.</i>

16:52.178 --> 16:54.138
Anyway, but nicely done.

16:54.138 --> 16:55.681
- Thank you.

16:55.681 --> 16:57.058
- All right, bladesmiths,

16:57.058 --> 16:58.893
in this slasher competition,

16:58.893 --> 17:01.687
we introduced you to the beast
that is this forge.

17:01.687 --> 17:03.397
You either survive
that nightmare,

17:03.397 --> 17:05.066
or you don't.

17:05.066 --> 17:06.901
The judges have made
their final decision.

17:06.901 --> 17:09.320
It's time for one of you
bladesmiths to leave The Forge.

17:09.320 --> 17:13.449
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:13.449 --> 17:16.702
David, your blade didn't make
the cut.

17:16.702 --> 17:18.704
- Well, David,
in chasing that forge weld

17:18.704 --> 17:21.123
you worked your steel very hot
for a long time,

17:21.123 --> 17:24.543
and that caused immense
grain growth inside your blade.

17:24.543 --> 17:26.712
That weakens your steel,
and our biggest concern

17:26.712 --> 17:29.715
is that it's now riddled
with cracks that are unfixable.

17:29.715 --> 17:32.134
- I understand,
and I agree.

17:32.134 --> 17:35.137
- David, you went down
swinging, but at this time,

17:35.137 --> 17:38.057
I have to ask you
to please surrender your blade.

17:38.057 --> 17:39.767
<i>- I agree with the judges.</i>

17:39.767 --> 17:41.769
<i>I'm going home 'cause cooked</i>
<i>my steel.</i>

17:41.769 --> 17:44.188
Forged it too hot,
and I got cracks

17:44.188 --> 17:46.148
before I even quenched it.

17:46.148 --> 17:47.650
<i>It was nice to hear</i>
<i>the judges appreciated</i>

17:47.650 --> 17:49.360
what I tried to do,
and, unfortunately,

17:49.360 --> 17:51.696
in this case,
there was no getting it done.

17:51.696 --> 17:53.030
<i>It was beyond repair.</i>

17:53.030 --> 17:55.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:55.700 --> 17:57.326
- All right, gents,
now that your blades

17:57.326 --> 17:59.036
have been tempered,
it's time to turn them

17:59.036 --> 18:00.788
into fully functional
slasher knives

18:00.788 --> 18:02.915
by attaching handles to them.

18:02.915 --> 18:05.543
Now, you'll have three hours
in this round.

18:05.543 --> 18:07.336
The nightmare continues.

18:07.336 --> 18:10.131
Gentlemen,
your time starts now.

18:10.131 --> 18:12.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:12.341 --> 18:14.719
Brandon, he's got a lot
of cracking in that blade.

18:14.719 --> 18:16.429
Dave, what can he do about it?

18:16.429 --> 18:17.930
- The crack on the edge

18:17.930 --> 18:19.849
is probably about
1/2 inch deep.

18:19.849 --> 18:22.476
He could actually re-profile
that edge and lose that crack.

18:22.476 --> 18:23.769
Crack on the back,
on the other hand,

18:23.769 --> 18:25.730
that's gonna need to be welded.

18:25.730 --> 18:28.816
<i>- So I have to re-profile</i>
<i>the front, the edge,</i>

18:28.816 --> 18:30.901
and then for the back
of the blade.

18:30.901 --> 18:32.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:32.320 --> 18:34.155
- Oh, no. No.
[chuckles]

18:34.155 --> 18:38.409
- You're saying, "No, no, no."
I'm like, "Yeah, yeah, yeah."

18:38.409 --> 18:40.161
Make that entire
spine serrated.

18:40.161 --> 18:41.704
That'll be evil-looking.

18:41.704 --> 18:43.748
It's getting scarier
and scarier in here.

18:43.748 --> 18:44.999
<i>- I ground out</i>
<i>these big grooves</i>

18:44.999 --> 18:46.584
<i>in the back of the blade,</i>

18:46.584 --> 18:47.960
<i>and I think it looks cool</i>
<i>as hell.</i>

18:47.960 --> 18:50.338
And it gets rid of the cracks.

18:50.338 --> 18:52.923
- The crack is deeper
than those little serrations.

18:52.923 --> 18:56.052
- I like it.
[laughs]

18:56.052 --> 18:59.639
But here, Tim--
he does have that one soft spot

18:59.639 --> 19:01.766
right on the edge of his blade.

19:01.766 --> 19:05.061
- The concern is right here
'cause it's a little thinner.

19:05.061 --> 19:07.063
And I'm working down to it,
and I don't want

19:07.063 --> 19:09.732
<i>to go anywhere past</i>
<i>where I'm already at</i>

19:09.732 --> 19:11.609
'cause I can get my blade
too thin,

19:11.609 --> 19:15.780
and that would be a weak point
and cause it to crack.

19:15.780 --> 19:17.823
<i>- Going through to round two</i>
<i>feels great.</i>

19:17.823 --> 19:19.950
<i>I feel like</i>
<i>I've made myself proud.</i>

19:19.950 --> 19:21.994
I need to add
some sort of hook

19:21.994 --> 19:23.621
<i>to fix my handle</i>
<i>where it doesn't</i>

19:23.621 --> 19:25.748
<i>slide out of the judge's hand.</i>

19:25.748 --> 19:27.458
- Well, Chase has come back

19:27.458 --> 19:29.168
with a piece
of angle iron here,

19:29.168 --> 19:32.088
so maybe he is gonna cut
a piece of scrap steel

19:32.088 --> 19:34.090
to weld onto that tang.
- Good deal.

19:34.090 --> 19:37.426
<i>- I'm planning a rounded</i>
<i>piece, sort of a hook shape.</i>

19:37.426 --> 19:39.470
I'm pretty confident
this is gonna work.

19:39.470 --> 19:41.806
<i>It's adding more mass</i>
<i>to the back of my blade,</i>

19:41.806 --> 19:43.891
as well as it's something
to hold the judge's hand.

19:43.891 --> 19:48.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:48.354 --> 19:50.398
- For my handle material
I've chosen Micarta.

19:50.398 --> 19:53.025
I use it a lot,
and it works well.

19:53.025 --> 19:54.777
I've always been a hunter.
I've always used knives.

19:54.777 --> 19:56.362
I've always loved knives.

19:56.362 --> 19:58.114
I got into making knives
because I wanted to make

19:58.114 --> 20:00.199
a knife that fits me.

20:00.199 --> 20:02.326
- Well, it looks like Brandon
has adjusted

20:02.326 --> 20:04.203
the size of his tang
a little bit.

20:04.203 --> 20:05.538
He's fitting up some

20:05.538 --> 20:07.248
rectangular scales
to it right now.

20:07.248 --> 20:09.250
- Yeah, it would be nice
to have some thick scales

20:09.250 --> 20:11.794
on there so that you can
actually get some retention,

20:11.794 --> 20:13.462
sort of flare it out
in the back of the handle.

20:13.462 --> 20:15.047
- Right. Right.

20:15.047 --> 20:16.382
<i>- I go to the drill press,</i>

20:16.382 --> 20:18.300
<i>and I try to drill the holes</i>

20:18.300 --> 20:20.636
through the handle material
that match the blade.

20:20.636 --> 20:22.555
Holy [bleep].

20:22.555 --> 20:24.348
Why are you not playing nice?

20:24.348 --> 20:26.434
This is kicking my ass.

20:26.434 --> 20:30.771
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

20:30.771 --> 20:32.773
<i>- Get everything done</i>
<i>with my pins,</i>

20:32.773 --> 20:34.608
<i>my scales, my blade's there.</i>

20:34.608 --> 20:36.110
I've got everything
ready to go.

20:36.110 --> 20:38.195
It's time to glue up
this handle.

20:38.195 --> 20:40.781
- Tim, looks like
he's got some epoxy

20:40.781 --> 20:43.033
that he just mixed up.

20:43.033 --> 20:44.994
<i>- Get the pins</i>
<i>on the first side.</i>

20:44.994 --> 20:46.912
<i>Go to put the second side on</i>

20:46.912 --> 20:48.998
<i>and realize I forgot</i>
<i>the clamps in the pantry.</i>

20:48.998 --> 20:50.583
[bleep].

20:50.583 --> 20:51.751
<i>It's five-minute epoxy.</i>

20:51.751 --> 20:53.085
- Man, oh, man.

20:53.085 --> 20:54.503
- I have to run over.

20:54.503 --> 20:56.255
I'm not sure
if I can get back in time

20:56.255 --> 20:57.882
<i>and get the other side on.</i>

20:57.882 --> 20:59.633
- Ay, yi, yi.

20:59.633 --> 21:01.844
Just one little mistake
can cost you your blade.

21:01.844 --> 21:05.181
- The epoxy will be set in
another minute and a half.

21:05.181 --> 21:06.544
- [bleep].

21:08.976 --> 21:10.853
<i>- I'm worried I've been</i>
<i>too long.</i>

21:10.853 --> 21:12.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:12.772 --> 21:15.608
I go get the clamps.
I get back.

21:15.608 --> 21:17.818
<i>Epoxy hasn't set up yet.</i>

21:17.818 --> 21:19.987
<i>Get it lined up on the pins</i>
<i>and start clamping her down,</i>

21:19.987 --> 21:22.364
<i>and I have just enough time</i>
<i>to get the second scale.</i>

21:22.364 --> 21:24.784
Whew. I got lucky.
[laughs]

21:24.784 --> 21:27.244
- Chase has been mucking around
with these pins

21:27.244 --> 21:29.955
and scales for a while now.

21:29.955 --> 21:32.082
<i>- The design I'm planning</i>
<i>for my handle</i>

21:32.082 --> 21:33.876
<i>is referred to as</i>
<i>a coke bottle.</i>

21:33.876 --> 21:35.878
It's swelled towards
the middle

21:35.878 --> 21:38.380
and narrowed in the front
and the back.

21:38.380 --> 21:40.257
- Hey, Chase,
there's some more clamps

21:40.257 --> 21:41.675
under there if you need 'em.

21:41.675 --> 21:43.010
- I think I might need
a couple more.

21:43.010 --> 21:44.595
- All right.
- Welcome to Clampville.

21:44.595 --> 21:46.222
Population, Chase.

21:46.222 --> 21:48.516
♪ ♪

21:48.516 --> 21:50.726
<i>- I got the handle on,</i>

21:50.726 --> 21:53.604
<i>and I grind finger grooves</i>
<i>in the handle.</i>

21:53.604 --> 21:55.231
When I get done,

21:55.231 --> 21:56.690
<i>I decided to check</i>
<i>the blade out,</i>

21:56.690 --> 21:58.317
and I see another crack.

21:58.317 --> 22:00.945
All right, we're not done,
I guess.

22:00.945 --> 22:03.614
- Ooh, what's he doing
on the spine?

22:03.614 --> 22:06.408
- He's recognized that
that crack goes deeper.

22:06.408 --> 22:09.411
<i>- The crack is about</i>
<i>five inches from the tip.</i>

22:09.411 --> 22:11.956
It's right in that sweet spot
for slashing.

22:11.956 --> 22:13.582
<i>If I don't fix it,</i>
<i>it'll break.</i>

22:13.582 --> 22:16.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:16.418 --> 22:19.547
- I can hear Tim grinding
on handle material.

22:19.547 --> 22:21.298
I can't see exactly what kind

22:21.298 --> 22:23.133
of a handle shape
he's got going.

22:23.133 --> 22:25.719
- Earlier, it looked like
it was kind of blocky,

22:25.719 --> 22:27.680
but then he's been doing
some shaping to his handle.

22:27.680 --> 22:28.931
So hopefully he puts
some contours

22:28.931 --> 22:30.432
to make it flow better.

22:30.432 --> 22:32.309
<i>- The handle is shaped,</i>

22:32.309 --> 22:34.687
<i>and then I just need</i>
<i>to get it polished up.</i>

22:34.687 --> 22:36.897
<i>Man, it's a sexy knife.</i>

22:36.897 --> 22:39.441
<i>I personally think it would</i>
<i>make a hell of a slasher.</i>

22:39.441 --> 22:41.193
It scares me.

22:41.193 --> 22:43.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:43.112 --> 22:45.948
- Well, Chase is doing a good
job of contouring his handle.

22:45.948 --> 22:49.285
He's got a nice palm swell
to wrap your hand around.

22:49.285 --> 22:51.704
- A little air chopping.
- Air chop. Oh, wow.

22:51.704 --> 22:53.455
[all grunting goofily]
- Stupid air.

22:53.455 --> 22:55.416
- Big air chop.

22:55.416 --> 22:57.251
<i>- I choose the shape</i>
<i>of the handle that I did</i>

22:57.251 --> 23:00.004
specifically because it fits
in one's hand a lot better.

23:00.004 --> 23:01.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:01.505 --> 23:03.716
- Ooh. No.

23:03.716 --> 23:05.467
- Big fish hook
on the end of the handle.

23:05.467 --> 23:08.721
- I do see that.
That could be a critical error.

23:08.721 --> 23:10.514
<i>- Going into these tests,</i>
<i>my biggest concern</i>

23:10.514 --> 23:12.850
is that my handle still
has problems,

23:12.850 --> 23:14.685
<i>but my blade</i>
<i>is just thick enough</i>

23:14.685 --> 23:16.145
for the hockey mask chop.

23:16.145 --> 23:23.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:23.277 --> 23:24.904
- Oh, no.
Uh-huh.

23:24.904 --> 23:27.114
[bleep].

23:27.114 --> 23:29.783
Frightening.
- Ah!

23:29.783 --> 23:32.745
- Five, four, three,

23:32.745 --> 23:34.413
two, one.

23:34.413 --> 23:36.290
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

23:36.290 --> 23:38.751
This round is over.

23:38.751 --> 23:45.549
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:50.554 --> 23:53.098
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test...

23:53.098 --> 23:54.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:54.892 --> 23:56.435
The hockey mask chop.

23:56.435 --> 23:58.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:58.479 --> 24:00.147
Horror movies,
when I was a kid,

24:00.147 --> 24:01.607
scared the bejeezus
out of me.

24:01.607 --> 24:03.442
And today I get my revenge.

24:03.442 --> 24:05.778
To test the strength
and durability of your knives,

24:05.778 --> 24:07.279
as well as
the overall construction,

24:07.279 --> 24:09.239
I'll be bashing them
into these hockey masks.

24:09.239 --> 24:10.866
Remember,
this test is all about

24:10.866 --> 24:12.576
what the masks do to
your knives

24:12.576 --> 24:14.954
and not when your knives
do to the masks.

24:14.954 --> 24:16.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:16.580 --> 24:18.040
Tim, you're up first.
You ready?

24:18.040 --> 24:19.291
- Yes, I am.
- All right.

24:19.291 --> 24:21.085
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:21.085 --> 24:22.836
<i>- I'm feeling pretty good</i>
<i>about my blade.</i>

24:22.836 --> 24:24.546
I'm just concerned
that the edge is

24:24.546 --> 24:26.966
a little too thin
for the chopping test.

24:26.966 --> 24:33.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:38.727 --> 24:40.396
Oh, man.

24:40.396 --> 24:42.314
- Well, Tim,
the edge you put on here

24:42.314 --> 24:43.774
is really fine.

24:43.774 --> 24:45.776
And, unfortunately,
what happened

24:45.776 --> 24:48.320
was it's taken up
a bunch of roll

24:48.320 --> 24:50.572
<i>right in the area</i>
<i>where I was hitting.</i>

24:50.572 --> 24:52.157
It's pretty significant.

24:52.157 --> 24:54.827
I can get my fingernail
underneath on both sides.

24:54.827 --> 24:56.912
That being said,
the rest of the blade held up.

24:56.912 --> 24:59.623
It's as straight as it was.

24:59.623 --> 25:00.874
It's all in one piece.
Well done.

25:00.874 --> 25:02.209
- Thank you.

25:02.209 --> 25:03.544
- Chase, you're up.
You ready?

25:03.544 --> 25:05.254
- Let's do it.
- All right.

25:05.254 --> 25:08.007
<i>- Ah, I'm very nervous.</i>

25:08.007 --> 25:09.967
<i>Seeing what it's done</i>
<i>to Tim's blade already,</i>

25:09.967 --> 25:11.927
I don't know what's gonna
happen to mine.

25:11.927 --> 25:13.739
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:24.690 --> 25:26.191
Hell, yeah.

25:26.191 --> 25:28.235
- Well, Chase,
your edge held up perfectly.

25:28.235 --> 25:31.447
There's no marks, no dings,
nothing on that edge.

25:31.447 --> 25:33.949
The handle--I know you put
in this hook for retention,

25:33.949 --> 25:36.243
but it's really narrow here.

25:36.243 --> 25:39.121
It puts my pinky in a weird
spot when I'm holding it.

25:39.121 --> 25:41.248
Other than that,
the blade held up beautifully.

25:41.248 --> 25:42.875
It's dead straight.

25:42.875 --> 25:44.877
Well done.
- Thank you.

25:44.877 --> 25:46.754
- Well, Brandon, You're up.
Are you ready?

25:46.754 --> 25:49.298
- Yes, sir.

25:49.298 --> 25:51.216
<i>I made my blade</i>
<i>to kill zombies.</i>

25:51.216 --> 25:53.677
<i>I can't help but wonder</i>
<i>if the cracks are gonna</i>

25:53.677 --> 25:55.929
show back up,
but I'm super excited.

25:55.929 --> 26:02.853
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:05.981 --> 26:09.068
Right on.
That's awesome.

26:09.068 --> 26:10.819
- Brandon, the mask took
a little nibble

26:10.819 --> 26:12.780
out of the corner
of your blade here,

26:12.780 --> 26:14.615
but I would have liked
to have seen

26:14.615 --> 26:16.533
a little more refinement
on this handle.

26:16.533 --> 26:18.285
It could have been
more comfortable,

26:18.285 --> 26:21.413
but all in all,
you're all in one piece.

26:21.413 --> 26:23.373
Well done.
- Thank you.

26:23.373 --> 26:27.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:27.169 --> 26:29.505
- Bladesmiths,
it's time to find out

26:29.505 --> 26:31.924
if your weapons
still have an edge.

26:31.924 --> 26:33.884
This is the sharpness test--

26:33.884 --> 26:35.511
the leather mask slice.

26:35.511 --> 26:37.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:37.596 --> 26:39.348
Now, unlike the strength test,

26:39.348 --> 26:41.558
this is all about what the edge
of your blade does

26:41.558 --> 26:43.894
to these leather masks.

26:43.894 --> 26:45.562
Heads up.
Tim, you're up first.

26:45.562 --> 26:47.189
You ready?
- I am.

26:47.189 --> 26:48.607
- Let's do this.

26:48.607 --> 26:55.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:03.330 --> 27:04.957
- Awesome.

27:04.957 --> 27:08.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:08.127 --> 27:09.670
- All right, Tim.

27:09.670 --> 27:13.090
This tip will penetrate
deep and easily

27:13.090 --> 27:15.592
into this leather mask.

27:15.592 --> 27:18.428
This slasher blade will cut.

27:18.428 --> 27:20.305
- Thank you.

27:20.305 --> 27:22.057
- All right, Chase, your turn.
You ready for this?

27:22.057 --> 27:23.183
- Let's do it.

27:23.183 --> 27:29.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:29.940 --> 27:31.149
Oh, nice.

27:31.149 --> 27:37.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:37.781 --> 27:39.825
Hell, yeah.
Nice.

27:39.825 --> 27:42.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:42.744 --> 27:44.329
- All right, Chase,

27:44.329 --> 27:46.623
let's talk about
your slasher blade right here.

27:46.623 --> 27:48.292
I love the balance
of this blade.

27:48.292 --> 27:51.044
It's easy to stab
and slash with it,

27:51.044 --> 27:53.005
and, most importantly...

27:53.005 --> 27:54.339
it will cut.

27:54.339 --> 27:55.757
- Thank you.

27:55.757 --> 27:57.092
- All right, Brandon,
you're up next.

27:57.092 --> 27:58.969
You ready?
- Hell, yeah. Let's do it.

27:58.969 --> 28:05.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:10.105 --> 28:11.481
[chuckles]
Right on.

28:11.481 --> 28:15.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:15.444 --> 28:16.904
That is awesome.

28:16.904 --> 28:19.156
<i>[shrieking]</i>

28:19.156 --> 28:20.407
That's quite the scream.

28:20.407 --> 28:21.867
- [laughs]

28:21.867 --> 28:24.703
- Brandon,
this is an intimidator.

28:24.703 --> 28:27.623
Your edge is sharp enough

28:27.623 --> 28:30.834
to open up a big gasp.

28:30.834 --> 28:33.253
Overall, sir,
your slasher blade--

28:33.253 --> 28:35.088
it will cut.

28:35.088 --> 28:36.965
- Thank you.

28:36.965 --> 28:38.342
- All right, bladesmiths,

28:38.342 --> 28:40.218
the judges have made
a final decision.

28:40.218 --> 28:42.596
It's time for one of you guys
to leave The Forge.

28:42.596 --> 28:44.848
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

28:44.848 --> 28:48.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:48.352 --> 28:50.938
Tim, your blade didn't
make the cut.

28:50.938 --> 28:52.481
- Tim, in the strength test,

28:52.481 --> 28:54.316
your blade developed
a rolled edge,

28:54.316 --> 28:56.777
and that really affected you
in the sharpness test.

28:56.777 --> 28:58.278
That's why
we got to let you go.

28:58.278 --> 29:00.113
- I understand.

29:00.113 --> 29:02.699
- Tim, please surrender
your blade.

29:02.699 --> 29:04.618
- I'm not upset
with the judges' decision

29:04.618 --> 29:06.912
because I did take more damage.

29:06.912 --> 29:08.413
<i>I was hoping maybe make it</i>
<i>to the finals</i>

29:08.413 --> 29:10.332
<i>like my brother did.</i>

29:10.332 --> 29:12.042
So he gets the bragging rights.

29:12.042 --> 29:13.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:13.961 --> 29:16.588
First thing I want
to do when I get home is...

29:16.588 --> 29:18.924
<i>probably feed my cat.</i>
<i>[chuckles]</i>

29:18.924 --> 29:21.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.343 --> 29:22.970
- Chase, Brandon,
when you guys showed up

29:22.970 --> 29:25.305
to this "Forged in Fire"
competition

29:25.305 --> 29:28.558
we gave you
a slasher blade challenge.

29:28.558 --> 29:30.477
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

29:30.477 --> 29:34.106
to re-create an iconic
horrible weapon from history.

29:34.106 --> 29:35.941
That weapon is...

29:35.941 --> 29:38.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:38.986 --> 29:40.946
A Grim Reaper scythe.

29:40.946 --> 29:43.573
- Oh, no.
- [laughs]

29:43.573 --> 29:45.867
Oh, that's great.

29:45.867 --> 29:47.411
<i>- The Grim Reaper scythe</i>

29:47.411 --> 29:49.496
<i>is the grisly weapon</i>
<i>of Death,</i>

29:49.496 --> 29:51.415
<i>whose legend traces</i>
<i>back to the dark days</i>

29:51.415 --> 29:54.710
<i>of the bubonic plague</i>
<i>in the 14th century.</i>

29:54.710 --> 29:57.295
<i>At that time, scythes were</i>
<i>common farm implements</i>

29:57.295 --> 29:59.339
<i>whose razor-sharp blades</i>
<i>were used to reap</i>

29:59.339 --> 30:01.717
<i>large fields of grass</i>
<i>or crops.</i>

30:01.717 --> 30:03.927
<i>So it's natural</i>
<i>that they would be recast</i>

30:03.927 --> 30:05.554
<i>as Death's tool,</i>

30:05.554 --> 30:07.889
<i>since he is the reaper</i>
<i>of souls.</i>

30:07.889 --> 30:09.725
<i>Occasionally,</i>
<i>rebellious peasants</i>

30:09.725 --> 30:11.351
<i>would also turn</i>
<i>their deadly scythes</i>

30:11.351 --> 30:15.313
<i>on each other as lethal</i>
<i>offensive weapons.</i>

30:15.313 --> 30:17.190
<i>Scythes feature</i>
<i>a large curved blade</i>

30:17.190 --> 30:19.985
<i>jutting from the top</i>
<i>of the shaft, or snath,</i>

30:19.985 --> 30:22.821
<i>and two short handles</i>
<i>for gripping.</i>

30:22.821 --> 30:24.948
<i>In popular culture,</i>
<i>scythes are now</i>

30:24.948 --> 30:27.075
<i>the prevalent symbol</i>
<i>for death...</i>

30:27.075 --> 30:29.995
<i>as evidenced in movies ranging</i>
<i>from "The Frighteners"</i>

30:29.995 --> 30:31.455
<i>to "Bill and Ted's</i>
<i>Bogus Journey"</i>

30:31.455 --> 30:32.998
<i>to "The Meaning of Life."</i>

30:32.998 --> 30:35.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:35.709 --> 30:38.545
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters--

30:38.545 --> 30:40.255
<i>the length of your blade</i>

30:40.255 --> 30:42.674
<i>must be between</i>
<i>24 and 26 inches in length</i>

30:42.674 --> 30:44.760
<i>and sharpened</i>
<i>on the inside curve.</i>

30:44.760 --> 30:47.721
<i>The socket of your blade must</i>
<i>be between 8 and 9 inches.</i>

30:47.721 --> 30:49.598
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of the shaft</i>

30:49.598 --> 30:52.809
<i>must be between</i>
<i>70 and 73 inches,</i>

30:52.809 --> 30:55.187
<i>and you must include</i>
<i>two handles</i>

30:55.187 --> 30:58.065
<i>and have a straight shaft.</i>

30:58.065 --> 31:00.233
<i>- I have never made</i>
<i>a blade like this.</i>

31:00.233 --> 31:02.694
<i>It's large, it's long,</i>

31:02.694 --> 31:04.488
it's completely
out of my wheelhouse

31:04.488 --> 31:06.615
of things that I make.

31:06.615 --> 31:08.784
- Bladesmiths,
you will five days

31:08.784 --> 31:10.952
at your home forge in which
to complete this challenge.

31:10.952 --> 31:12.913
At the end of those five days,
you will return

31:12.913 --> 31:15.499
and present your scythes
to our panel of expert judges.

31:15.499 --> 31:18.126
Only after they've tested them
to hell and back

31:18.126 --> 31:20.545
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

31:20.545 --> 31:23.048
who walks out of here
with a check for 10 grand.

31:23.048 --> 31:25.008
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

31:25.008 --> 31:27.135
- Good luck.
- Good luck, man.

31:27.135 --> 31:29.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:29.596 --> 31:32.349
<i>- I'm back in Blackfoot,</i>
<i>Idaho, at my home forge.</i>

31:32.349 --> 31:34.684
I'm gonna build
two complete scythes.

31:34.684 --> 31:37.813
<i>It'll be a little complicated</i>
<i>to forge two different blades,</i>

31:37.813 --> 31:40.065
<i>but I want a backup.</i>

31:40.065 --> 31:42.818
<i>I want to make sure I have a</i>
<i>blade for the judges to judge.</i>

31:42.818 --> 31:44.569
<i>So, at this point,</i>
<i>I'm just trying</i>

31:44.569 --> 31:46.238
<i>to get the steel drawn out,</i>

31:46.238 --> 31:48.448
<i>flattened out</i>
<i>to where I need it to be.</i>

31:48.448 --> 31:51.576
<i>I'm making it way longer than</i>
<i>I should so I can cut it off.</i>

31:51.576 --> 31:53.370
<i>It's a lot easier to have</i>
<i>too much material</i>

31:53.370 --> 31:55.122
<i>than not enough.</i>

31:55.122 --> 31:58.125
I just did that
to get the scale off

31:58.125 --> 31:59.668
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:59.668 --> 32:01.837
I'm gonna put
a nice curve in that.

32:01.837 --> 32:03.463
<i>I'm gonna finish grinding</i>
<i>this one</i>

32:03.463 --> 32:05.340
<i>and see how it turns out,</i>

32:05.340 --> 32:07.217
<i>'cause it looks like there</i>
<i>might be a crack,</i>

32:07.217 --> 32:09.344
<i>and after round one,</i>
<i>I don't want another crack.</i>

32:09.344 --> 32:14.307
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:14.307 --> 32:16.017
- I was about nine years old,

32:16.017 --> 32:18.687
and I bought my first knife
with my own money.

32:18.687 --> 32:21.481
And then for Christmas
one year, I got a forge.

32:21.481 --> 32:24.025
<i>It was just</i>
<i>a small coal forge.</i>

32:24.025 --> 32:26.611
And then I came in contact
with a mastersmith,

32:26.611 --> 32:28.905
<i>and pretty much</i>
<i>everything I know now</i>

32:28.905 --> 32:30.448
about making knives
I learned from him.

32:30.448 --> 32:33.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:33.076 --> 32:34.828
<i>Working this blade</i>
<i>is really cumbersome,</i>

32:34.828 --> 32:36.663
<i>and it hangs off a lot,</i>

32:36.663 --> 32:38.832
<i>so it's really hard to get</i>
<i>a good hold on it.</i>

32:38.832 --> 32:40.792
<i>I don't want to use the</i>
<i>power hammer for everything</i>

32:40.792 --> 32:42.377
<i>'cause I don't want it</i>
<i>to get away from me.</i>

32:42.377 --> 32:44.588
I've been having a lot of
trouble with it today.

32:44.588 --> 32:47.007
<i>So I'm trying to do</i>
<i>a lot by hand now.</i>

32:47.007 --> 32:50.177
<i>I think I'm gonna start trying</i>
<i>to let the blade normalize</i>

32:50.177 --> 32:51.887
<i>and cool down slowly,</i>

32:51.887 --> 32:53.388
where I can start grinding
on the big grinder.

32:53.388 --> 32:56.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:56.600 --> 32:58.894
<i>I think I'm calling it</i>
<i>a day for today.</i>

32:58.894 --> 33:00.979
<i>I'm really happy</i>
<i>with my progress.</i>

33:00.979 --> 33:02.856
<i>- At the end of day one,</i>

33:02.856 --> 33:04.900
<i>it looks like there's</i>
<i>a crack in the blade,</i>

33:04.900 --> 33:06.735
<i>but after I get done grinding,</i>
<i>there's no crack.</i>

33:06.735 --> 33:08.486
<i>It was just</i>
<i>a piece of material</i>

33:08.486 --> 33:10.530
<i>coming off the belt,</i>
<i>but it scared me.</i>

33:10.530 --> 33:13.617
So the biggest problem I see
is they're so long,

33:13.617 --> 33:16.953
<i>and anytime you get steel</i>
<i>that hot, to quench it,</i>

33:16.953 --> 33:19.331
<i>it wants to bend a little bit.</i>

33:19.331 --> 33:23.210
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:23.210 --> 33:24.502
<i>Damn fire.</i>

33:24.502 --> 33:26.963
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:26.963 --> 33:29.049
Good thing I got
a fire pit out here.

33:29.049 --> 33:32.010
[exhales sharply, laughs]

33:32.010 --> 33:34.554
No, was not expecting that.

33:34.554 --> 33:36.806
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:36.806 --> 33:38.767
I am ready to weld
the blade to the socket.

33:38.767 --> 33:41.895
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:41.895 --> 33:43.313
<i>So far, so good.</i>

33:43.313 --> 33:44.856
<i>I'm working with maple here,</i>

33:44.856 --> 33:46.483
<i>and you stick</i>
<i>it through there,</i>

33:46.483 --> 33:48.026
<i>and it turns it</i>
<i>into one thickness,</i>

33:48.026 --> 33:49.444
<i>and it just looks cool</i>
<i>as hell.</i>

33:49.444 --> 33:53.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:53.406 --> 33:55.116
Now we let it dry,

33:55.116 --> 33:57.202
'cause this bad boy
is just about done.

33:57.202 --> 33:58.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:58.495 --> 34:00.413
<i>- I'm feeling great.</i>

34:00.413 --> 34:01.873
<i>I feel like my progress</i>
<i>is moving right along.</i>

34:01.873 --> 34:03.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:03.667 --> 34:05.877
Quench went awesome.

34:05.877 --> 34:07.671
<i>Just some slight warping</i>
<i>on the edge,</i>

34:07.671 --> 34:10.173
but nothing I can't fix
during grinding.

34:10.173 --> 34:13.468
<i>I'm using this piece of steel</i>
<i>to create my socket.</i>

34:13.468 --> 34:16.554
I don't have the right tool
to kind of bend it around,

34:16.554 --> 34:19.015
<i>but I finally get the socket</i>
<i>close to done.</i>

34:19.015 --> 34:22.143
<i>So I check my parameters to</i>
<i>make sure everything's right,</i>

34:22.143 --> 34:24.646
<i>and I realize that my socket</i>

34:24.646 --> 34:28.233
<i>is not even barely meeting</i>
<i>parameters.</i>

34:28.233 --> 34:32.362
Okay, so I guess I must have
messed that up pretty bad.

34:32.362 --> 34:33.780
What I've been working on

34:33.780 --> 34:36.074
for the past few hours
is just garbage.

34:36.074 --> 34:38.618
All right, I'm done for today.

34:38.618 --> 34:40.427
I got to start over.

34:43.550 --> 34:44.207
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:44.207 --> 34:46.918
<i>- I had a setback yesterday</i>
<i>with my socket.</i>

34:46.918 --> 34:48.753
Ah...ah.

34:48.753 --> 34:50.630
<i>Instead of trying</i>
<i>to completely fabricate</i>

34:50.630 --> 34:52.799
<i>my socket from scratch,</i>
<i>I'm gonna be using a pipe.</i>

34:52.799 --> 34:54.926
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:54.926 --> 34:57.721
<i>Now that I have my socket</i>
<i>ground to shape and size,</i>

34:57.721 --> 34:59.514
I need to measure it.

34:59.514 --> 35:02.267
I'm gonna do this probably
a couple hundred times

35:02.267 --> 35:05.353
just to make sure
I'm not short again,

35:05.353 --> 35:07.606
'cause making that mistake
a second time

35:07.606 --> 35:09.816
would just be ridiculous.

35:09.816 --> 35:12.569
<i>- Choosing the weapon</i>
<i>out of the two that I made,</i>

35:12.569 --> 35:14.112
<i>it's the one</i>
<i>that looks the best,</i>

35:14.112 --> 35:15.822
<i>that performs the best,</i>

35:15.822 --> 35:18.617
and this is
a pretty sweet weapon.

35:18.617 --> 35:21.745
Just got a little bit
of finish work to do,

35:21.745 --> 35:24.998
so I'm gonna go spend
some time with my family.

35:24.998 --> 35:27.667
- I don't want, like,
a regular farm tool,

35:27.667 --> 35:30.378
so I am bluing the blade.

35:30.378 --> 35:32.464
Trying to go for that definite
Grim Reaper vibe.

35:32.464 --> 35:33.965
This kind of dark complexion,

35:33.965 --> 35:35.508
paired along
with the handle,

35:35.508 --> 35:37.260
which I'm also gonna
stain black,

35:37.260 --> 35:40.347
it just gives it an overall,
a lot more menacing look.

35:40.347 --> 35:43.183
It looks a lot more evil,
a lot more cool.

35:43.183 --> 35:46.311
To finish up
my Grim Reaper scythe,

35:46.311 --> 35:48.313
I did an engraving of Death

35:48.313 --> 35:51.483
accompanied by ravens
on the socket.

35:51.483 --> 35:54.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:54.694 --> 35:58.239
It's definitely
a heavy thing to swing, but...

35:58.239 --> 36:00.033
yeah, I'd say it works.

36:00.033 --> 36:06.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:06.164 --> 36:10.043
- Chase, Brandon,
welcome back to The Forge.

36:10.043 --> 36:13.088
You fellas have had five days
at your home forges to work

36:13.088 --> 36:15.882
on your Grim Reaper scythes.

36:15.882 --> 36:17.676
Chase, how did it go?
- It went great for me.

36:17.676 --> 36:19.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:19.344 --> 36:21.638
<i>My blade is constructed</i>
<i>out of 52100.</i>

36:21.638 --> 36:25.600
<i>The handle is white oak</i>
<i>with a mild steel socket.</i>

36:25.600 --> 36:27.560
- All right, Brandon,
how'd it go for you?

36:27.560 --> 36:30.063
- It went great.

36:30.063 --> 36:32.816
<i>The blade is</i>
<i>1080 plow spring steel.</i>

36:32.816 --> 36:34.442
<i>The handles are constructed</i>

36:34.442 --> 36:35.735
<i>with a mortise and tenon</i>
<i>joint,</i>

36:35.735 --> 36:37.654
<i>so it's strong as hell.</i>

36:37.654 --> 36:39.531
- All right, gentlemen,
there will be a strength test,

36:39.531 --> 36:41.074
a sharpness test,

36:41.074 --> 36:44.202
and up first...
a chilling kill test.

36:44.202 --> 36:46.579
Doug.

36:46.579 --> 36:49.082
- Bladesmiths,
this is the kill test.

36:49.082 --> 36:51.334
The Grim Reaper uses the scythe

36:51.334 --> 36:53.920
to harvest the souls of humans
when it's their time.

36:53.920 --> 36:56.840
To test the lethality
of your scythe,

36:56.840 --> 36:58.800
I will take your scythe

36:58.800 --> 37:02.178
and try to rip out the soul
of these ballistics dummies.

37:02.178 --> 37:04.013
Chase, you're up first.
You ready?

37:04.013 --> 37:06.015
- Ready as I'll ever be.
- Let's do this.

37:06.015 --> 37:07.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:07.684 --> 37:09.018
<i>- I'm feeling really pumped</i>

37:09.018 --> 37:10.437
<i>and confident going into this,</i>

37:10.437 --> 37:11.896
<i>and I'm just really ready</i>

37:11.896 --> 37:13.273
to see it tear
this dummy apart.

37:13.273 --> 37:20.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.031 --> 37:23.616
- [chuckles]
- Oh.

37:23.616 --> 37:30.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:37.380 --> 37:38.590
Damn.

37:38.590 --> 37:44.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:44.220 --> 37:46.431
- All right, Chase, let's talk
about your scythe right here.

37:46.431 --> 37:48.975
The edge is sharp.

37:48.975 --> 37:51.644
Your tips punctures deep,
breaking ribs,

37:51.644 --> 37:54.564
and right into the heart,
pulling out its soul.

37:54.564 --> 37:57.609
This weapon, sir--
it will kill.

37:57.609 --> 37:59.486
Good job.
- Thank you.

37:59.486 --> 38:01.070
- All right, Brandon,
your turn.

38:01.070 --> 38:02.363
You ready?
- Yes, sir.

38:02.363 --> 38:04.282
- Let's do this.
- Let's do it.

38:04.282 --> 38:05.784
<i>I'm pretty nervous,</i>

38:05.784 --> 38:07.494
<i>but I'm excited</i>
<i>at the same time</i>

38:07.494 --> 38:09.329
<i>because I think</i>
<i>the ballistics dummy test</i>

38:09.329 --> 38:11.623
is one of the coolest tests
I've ever seen.

38:11.623 --> 38:18.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:21.049 --> 38:22.801
[chuckles]

38:22.801 --> 38:29.724
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:29.724 --> 38:31.226
[laughs]

38:31.226 --> 38:33.937
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:33.937 --> 38:36.314
That was awesome.

38:36.314 --> 38:37.899
- All right, Brandon,

38:37.899 --> 38:39.818
let's talk about your scythe
right here.

38:39.818 --> 38:42.028
Aside from reaping the soul
out of this ballistics dummy,

38:42.028 --> 38:44.614
it seemed to have taken the
clavicle and sternum with it.

38:44.614 --> 38:46.783
Your point here really digs in,

38:46.783 --> 38:48.660
but in doing so
and hitting the bone,

38:48.660 --> 38:50.912
<i>you have a little chip</i>
<i>right here at the tip...</i>

38:50.912 --> 38:52.455
- Oh, no.

38:52.455 --> 38:54.874
- And one on the blade
right there,

38:54.874 --> 38:58.253
but, most importantly,
it will kill.

38:58.253 --> 39:00.004
- There it is.
Thank you, sir.

39:00.004 --> 39:03.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:03.007 --> 39:04.843
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

39:04.843 --> 39:07.011
To test the strength
and durability of your scythes,

39:07.011 --> 39:09.347
I've affixed them
to our "Forged in Fire" coffin.

39:09.347 --> 39:10.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:10.932 --> 39:12.809
- Oh, God.

39:12.809 --> 39:16.145
- And I will batoning
your edge many, many times.

39:16.145 --> 39:17.939
Remember,
this test is all about

39:17.939 --> 39:19.691
what the batons
do to the scythes

39:19.691 --> 39:21.651
and not what the scythes
do to the batons

39:21.651 --> 39:22.902
Chase, you're up first.
You ready?

39:22.902 --> 39:24.445
- All right.
[chuckles]

39:24.445 --> 39:27.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:27.615 --> 39:29.993
<i>I'm immediately worried.</i>

39:29.993 --> 39:32.954
<i>Bone can really destroy</i>
<i>even the best of blades.</i>

39:32.954 --> 39:34.455
- [sighs]

39:34.455 --> 39:35.874
- [chuckles]

39:35.874 --> 39:38.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:48.678 --> 39:52.056
- Whoa!
[metal clanging]

39:52.056 --> 39:56.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:56.936 --> 39:59.522
Chase, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

39:59.522 --> 40:01.941
on the fourth strike.

40:01.941 --> 40:04.110
You know what that means,
right?

40:04.110 --> 40:07.280
We can no longer continue
testing your blade.

40:07.280 --> 40:10.867
However, Brandon,
your blade needs to survive

40:10.867 --> 40:13.828
four strikes of that baton
in order for you

40:13.828 --> 40:15.788
to become
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

40:15.788 --> 40:17.582
Ben...

40:17.582 --> 40:19.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:19.500 --> 40:21.252
- [sighs]
- Brandon, you ready for this?

40:21.252 --> 40:22.879
- Yes, sir, let's do it.
- All right.

40:22.879 --> 40:26.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:26.507 --> 40:28.551
- I'm scared.

40:28.551 --> 40:31.012
<i>I'm just hoping I can make it</i>
<i>through four strikes.</i>

40:31.012 --> 40:36.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:38.561 --> 40:39.938
[bleep], yeah.

40:39.938 --> 40:44.025
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:44.025 --> 40:47.695
- Brandon, congratulations.
Your blade survived.

40:47.695 --> 40:49.739
Chase, unfortunately,
your blade has suffered

40:49.739 --> 40:51.491
a catastrophic weapons failure

40:51.491 --> 40:53.618
and will no longer continue
in this competition,

40:53.618 --> 40:55.912
and for that reason,
I have to ask you

40:55.912 --> 40:57.121
to please shake
your competitor's hand

40:57.121 --> 40:58.665
and leave The Forge.

40:58.665 --> 41:00.249
- Good job, man.
- Good job.

41:00.249 --> 41:01.918
<i>- I'm very proud</i>
<i>of my scythe.</i>

41:01.918 --> 41:03.378
It was the best work

41:03.378 --> 41:05.004
that I possibly
could have done.

41:05.004 --> 41:07.715
<i>I've learned a lot</i>
<i>about myself personally</i>

41:07.715 --> 41:09.884
and the ways that I work
under pressure.

41:09.884 --> 41:12.053
<i>And I had a really great time</i>
<i>doing all this.</i>

41:12.053 --> 41:14.263
Right now it's kind of hard
to express that,

41:14.263 --> 41:17.058
<i>but I really have had</i>
<i>a great time.</i>

41:17.058 --> 41:20.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:20.311 --> 41:21.854
- Brandon, congratulations.

41:21.854 --> 41:24.148
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

41:24.148 --> 41:27.485
and you'll be reaping
a check for $10,000.

41:27.485 --> 41:28.820
Good job, brother.
- Thank you so much.

41:28.820 --> 41:30.697
Hell, yeah. I love it.

41:30.697 --> 41:32.281
<i>I feel great.</i>

41:32.281 --> 41:34.951
This is absolutely
unbelievable to me.

41:34.951 --> 41:36.869
<i>I mean, I want to say</i>
<i>to my family,</i>

41:36.869 --> 41:39.747
"Guys, I did it,
and I'm coming home."

41:39.747 --> 41:42.500
My name's Brandon Williams.
I'm from Blackfoot, Idaho.

41:42.500 --> 41:44.377
<i>I'm the new</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

41:44.377 --> 41:45.503
Hell, yeah!

41:45.503 --> 41:50.425
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:50.425 --> 41:53.261
<i>[sinister laughter]</i>
